Curiouser Operations System
A browser-based weekly reporting and analytics platform for Curiouser early years education centres.

What this is
A single HTML file that runs in any browser — no installation, no server, no subscription. Staff open it on their phone or laptop, fill in their section of the weekly report, and the dashboard updates instantly with charts, trends, and anomaly flags across all centres.

Built as a working prototype to validate the reporting workflow before commissioning a hosted multi-user version.

What it does
Reporting
Staff submit weekly operational data through clean, role-based input forms. Each person sees only the section they own:

General — safety incidents, revenue bookings by product type (Silver/Gold/Platinum CP, trials, one-offs, camps, parties), and club footfall
Classes — per-class attendance, cancellations, trials, returners, and CP conversions across all 17 class types
Events & Parties — party and event attendance, enquiries, and camp bookings and utilisation by centre
Marketing — Instagram and Rednotes weekly performance including views, likes, messages, new followers, investment, and best/worst posts
Weekly Dashboard
Real-time view of the selected week with week-on-week deltas:

6 headline KPIs with directional arrows (venue attendance, class attendance, total bookings, attendance rate, CP conversion, cancellation rate)
Attendance trend line chart across all weeks
Booking mix breakdown (stacked bar + table)
Classes ranked by attendance rate with colour-coded bars
Marketing reach comparison (Instagram vs Rednotes)
Automatic anomaly flags
Monthly Analytics
Aggregated view across all weeks in a selected month, with side-by-side comparison to the previous month:

Monthly KPIs with month-on-month deltas
Full detail summary card for both months
Weekly attendance trend chart within the month
Month-on-month grouped bar chart for headline metrics
Booking mix for both months
Class performance table with attendance rates and MoM delta column
Marketing summary (IG vs Rednotes) with previous month comparison
All anomaly flags for the month, sorted by severity
Anomaly Flag Engine
Automatically surfaces issues each week without anyone having to look for them:

High cancellation rate weeks (≥30% red, ≥20% amber)
Class cancelled streak detection (flags any class not running for 2+ consecutive weeks)
CP conversion below floor (flags when trial-to-CP conversion drops below 5%)
Venue attendance drop vs 4-week rolling average (>20% triggers red)
Zero marketing activity weeks
Camp utilisation alerts (<20% red, <75% amber)
Trial-heavy class detection (flags when >60% of bookings in a class are trials — conversion watch)
Safety incidents and complaints always surface as red regardless of other thresholds
Archive
Full history of every submitted week with flag summary and direct links to the dashboard view for that week.

Centres and classes tracked
Centres: Hampstead · Kensington · WGC · St Mary

Classes: MM · MM WGC · MM KEN · MM St Mary · Baby Music · Music · Drama 2-4 · Drama 4-6 · Cooking 2-4 · Cooking 4-6 · Discoveries · Science 3-4 · Science 5-6 · Monty Maths · Private Class · Toddler Art · French

Instructors: Erry · Margot · Tegan · Joe · Erin

Tech stack
Layer	What
Runtime	Single HTML file, no build step
Language	Vanilla JavaScript (ES2020)
Styling	CSS custom properties, no framework
Charts	Hand-written SVG, no chart library
Storage	Browser localStorage
Fonts	Playfair Display + DM Sans via Google Fonts
Dependencies	None
The file is entirely self-contained. It works offline after the first load (Google Fonts requires a connection on first visit, then caches).

Limitations of this version
This is a prototype. It is designed to validate the reporting workflow with real staff before investing in a production system.

Limitation	Implication
Data lives in the browser	Each device has its own copy — no shared database
No user accounts	No access control or per-user history
No automatic sync	Tiger's marketing submission on his phone is not visible to the ops manager on their laptop
No server	Cannot send alerts, scheduled reports, or email PDFs automatically
No backup	Clearing browser history or using private browsing can lose data — use Export regularly
Data export
Two export options are available from the Dashboard:

Export CSV — flat weekly summary table, ready to paste into Google Sheets or Excel
Export JSON — complete structured data including per-class detail, camp rows, and marketing notes — use this as the migration file when moving to the hosted version
Seeded data
The file ships with four weeks of February 2026 data (WC 02.02 through WC 23.02) taken from the existing operation report. The dashboard and monthly analytics are functional from the first open.

Roadmap — hosted version
When the prototype has been validated with real staff, the next version should be commissioned as a proper hosted web application. The data model, form fields, and anomaly logic in this file serve as the full functional specification.

Recommended stack for the hosted version:

Frontend: React or Next.js (the existing HTML/JS translates directly)
Backend: Supabase or Firebase (handles auth, shared database, and real-time sync)
Auth: Google SSO (team already uses Google Workspace)
Hosting: Vercel or Netlify (free tier is sufficient at this scale)
Estimated build cost: £3,000–8,000 with a freelance developer using this file as the spec
Features to add in the hosted version that are out of scope for the prototype:

Role-based login (each staff member sees their own section on login)
Shared live database (submissions from any device visible to all)
Scheduled weekly PDF email to ops manager every Monday morning
Direct integration with booking system (Stripe / class booking backend) to auto-populate the revenue and footfall sections
Push notifications when a red flag is triggered
13-week rolling forecasts once sufficient history has accumulated
File structure
curiouser-site.html
│
├── <style>          Brand design system, CSS custom properties, all layout
│
├── <header>         Sticky nav bar — Home · Report · Dashboard · Monthly · Archive
│
├── #page-home       Landing page with KPI strip and role-based entry cards
├── #page-report     Input forms (General / Classes / Events & Parties / Marketing / Full)
├── #page-dashboard  Weekly charts, flags, and analysis
├── #page-monthly    Monthly aggregation and MoM comparison
├── #page-archive    Full submission history
│
└── <script>
    ├── CONSTANTS    Class list, instructor list, anomaly thresholds
    ├── SEED DATA    Feb 2026 pre-loaded data
    ├── STATE        localStorage load/save
    ├── NAVIGATION   showPage(), mobile drawer
    ├── HOME         renderHome(), KPI cards
    ├── FORM         openForm(), buildForm(), class cards, camp builder, submit
    ├── DASHBOARD    renderDashboard(), all chart renderers
    ├── MONTHLY      renderMonthly(), aggregateMonth(), MoM comparison
    ├── FLAGS        computeFlags() — anomaly detection engine
    ├── ARCHIVE      renderArchive()
    ├── EXPORT       exportCSV(), exportJSON()
    └── UTILS        totalBookings(), fmt(), pct(), toast()
Anomaly thresholds
All thresholds are defined as constants at the top of the script block and can be adjusted without touching any other code:

js
const THR = {
  attendanceDrop: 0.20,   // flag if venue attendance drops >20% vs 4-week avg
  cpConvFloor:    0.05,   // flag if CP conversion falls below 5%
  trialNoShow:    0.30,   // flag if >30% of trials don't attend
  cancelStreak:   2,      // flag a class not running for 2+ consecutive weeks
  revenueDrop:    0.15,   // flag if total bookings drop >15% vs 4-week avg
  igCpa:          1.00    // flag if Instagram cost-per-follower exceeds £1
};
Contributing / handoff notes
If you are a developer picking this up to build the hosted version:

The seed data object (SEED) in the script is the canonical data schema — every field name used in the forms, dashboard, and export maps directly to this structure
aggregateMonth() is the aggregation logic — port this to a database query or server-side function
computeFlags() is the anomaly engine — this should run server-side on each submission and store results, rather than computing on the fly in the browser
The CSS custom properties at the top of <style> are the complete brand token set — use these as the design system for the hosted frontend
Export a JSON file from the prototype before migrating — this becomes the seed data import for the production database





